<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Voice, Bjt,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Woman's Voice Will Count Down the Final Seconds</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Since <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> made his 15-minute suborbital flight aboard the Mercury capsule Freedom 7 in 1961, counting down the final seconds to launch has been a man's job. On Monday, <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> changes all that. The 27-year-old public affairs specialist with <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> will replace <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> as the voice of Shuttle Launch Control for the liftoff of Discovery. It will be the first time a woman has served as launch commentator for a flight carrying astronauts. Her job will be to guide the news media and the public through the anxious minutes before the main engines ignite in a burst of flame and smoke, until the shuttle clears the launch tower and communications switch to the Johnson Space Center in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. Her challenge to explain what is taking place behind the scenes and to translate the technical chatter among launch managers into `` something that anybody can understand.'' <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> is quick to contrast the significance of her new role with that of female astronauts. `` I think what they're doing is a lot more trendsetting and important than what a commentator does,'' she said, `` because they're actually doing it instead of reporting on what's been done.'' Nevertheless, <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> said, she likes to think her voice will be an inspiration to young women. `` If that would inspire somebody to go on and achieve what they want in life,'' she says, `` I think that is fantastic.'' <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> has worked for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> for seven years, rising to her position of space shuttle specialist from a college work-study program that started while she was earning a bachelor's degree in journalism from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION>. She edited the space center newsletter, Spaceport News, for three years before she was assigned to the space shuttle beat. Now, she attends several daily meetings of launch managers to stay up-to-date on the progress of work to get three orbiters and their external fuel tanks and booster rockets ready for flight. To prepare for her debut, <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> provided launch commentary for some unmanned Atlas Centaur and <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> launches and for the early portions of some shuttle countdowns. She has watched numerous launches from her seat at the firing room console beside <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, who is now deputy director for public affairs at Kennedy Space Center. She also hired a voice coach. Although she has learned the lingo and has carefully prepared a script, <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> knows her biggest challenge will be the `` real-time element of the job'' _ and how she'll react if there's an unexpected problem during the countdown. `` You're going to be scrambling to try and figure out what it is because you want to have the right story before you tell the world what's going on,'' <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> said.
