<SECOND>AM-Cave Woman, Bjt,0820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman in Isolation Experiment in Cave Lives Like Rat in a Cage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Time passes slowly for <PERSON> Stefania </PERSON> <PERSON> Follini </PERSON>. The Italian woman has fallen into a routine of staying awake 23 hours, then sleeping for 10, after being holed up in a cave for two months as part of a research project into the effects of isolation. She has no sun, radios or clocks to guide her sense of time, and little contact with other humans. `` Sunday, Feb. 12, 10 a.m.,'' Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> writes on a computer at a desk in her plastic habitat at one end of the cave. Actually, it's noon on Wednesday, March 8. On Jan. 13, the 27-year-old Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> climbed 30 feet below the earth's surface and into the 200-foot-long Lost Cave in the hills west of <LOCATION> Carlsbad </LOCATION> to begin a four - to five-month isolation experiment An Italian research group is sponsoring the experiment, along with various <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> universities and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. As she moves about in her two-room, 200-square-foot Plexiglas house, Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> resembles a laboratory rat in a cage. Researchers monitor her with three video cameras and microphones, and they type in occasional messages to her computer, but Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> can not see or hear another human. During her waking hours, she sometimes taps away at her computer like a subject in a <PERSON> B.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> experiment as researchers in a trailer above record the results of tests of her concentration, memory and reasoning ability. One thing researchers are discovering in isolation experiments _ intended, among other things, to give them insight into how humans might react on interplanetary space flights _ is that men tend to be more cheerful in long isolation than women. <PERSON> Maurizio </PERSON> <PERSON> Montalbini </PERSON>, the experiment coordinator who once spent six months isolated in a cave, alludes to that in a brief computer conversation in Italian with his fellow native of <PERSON> Ancona </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. `` You should change your sex,'' <PERSON> Montalbini </PERSON> writes to the glum-looking Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON>. `` You always seem like a sad one.'' `` I feel sadder some times than others,'' she replies. After chatting via computer for a little bit, <PERSON> Montalbini </PERSON> asks Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> to take the series of computerized mental tests, which she performs about once a week. Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON>, who had been interrupted from reading a novel to take the medical measurements and relay them by computer, becomes a little sarcastic. `` Great idea, like a dessert!'' she responds. An interior decorator by profession, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> has livened up her 10-by-10-foot living area with colorful figures cut out of construction paper and glued to the walls. Among the paper decorations: wine bottles, a flower box and a `` window,'' covered with blue paper lace curtains, that looks out onto a white paper moon and stars. A brown paper cat sits beside the windowsill. Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> spends much of her time kneeling on a blue mat, reading. She brought 400 books with her: novels, histories, English primers. She stays in shape by practicing judo moves. She is remarkably quiet. Even though researchers can hear her, she prefers to communicate with them by computer. She does talk a little to her pets _ two mice she dubbed <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nicoleta </PERSON>, and a salamander _ all found in the cave. She keeps a vigil to prevent the rodents from gnawing at cables or eating her food, which consists mostly of rice and beans she cooks on an electric stove. Long-term space flight might be a lot like this, except for the lack of gravity in space. Medical researchers are especially interested in finding out what isolation does to one's emotional and mental well-being. `` <PERSON> Stefania </PERSON> is fine,'' says <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvagno </PERSON>, an Italian doctor who alternates 24-hour monitoring shifts with <PERSON> Montalbini </PERSON>. `` As of now, she has n't expressed any desire that deals with the outside world.'' But it appears Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON>'s world is n't quite a utopia. She occasionally attaches electrodes to her head before she falls asleep so researchers can study her brain waves in various stages of sleep, and the results show symptoms of mild depression. <PERSON> Galvagno </PERSON> says he and <PERSON> Montalbini </PERSON> sometimes joke around with <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> to buoy her spirits. <PERSON> Montalbini </PERSON> says Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON>'s ability to concentrate has deteriorated. In previous experiments, people in isolation alone have improved their concentration, while members of groups isolated in caves have lost their concentration. About this time, around 4:30 p.m., Miss <PERSON> Follini </PERSON> walks over to her computer, types in `` Ciaoooooooo,'' waves to the video camera, dims the lights _ they always stay on _ lies on the mat under a blanket and stares at the camera a while. Presently she closes her eyes and falls asleep: <PERSON> Stefania </PERSON> <PERSON> Follini </PERSON>, a brown paper cat, two mice and a salamander.
