 the importance of the Tower debate to his own political fortunes even as he acknowledged judgments `` inevitably'' would be made on how he performed. After initially remaining in the background, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> assumed an increasingly prominent role in the confirmation struggle. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> learned Monday night that the votes were in hand to defeat Tower's nomination, and let the Republicans know by telling reporters on Tuesday. The following day _ Wednesday _ Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> became the third Democrat to announce his support of Tower. But then a string of three wavering Democrats quickly came to the floor and declared their opposition. The effect was to blunt the impact of <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s long-awaited decision and seal Tower's defeat. It all bore the marks of skillful behind-the-scenes stage managing. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> worked closely and several Republicans said it was the decision by the highly respected <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> to oppose Tower that made confirmation difficult to achieve. Yet when <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> himself came under attack from Republicans for detailing investigators from a subcommittee he heads to check out allegations against <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> came to his defense. `` We are not going to get in a position here where one, two, three, four, five, six, seven people come over here and ask the same question and the senator -LRB- <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> -RRB- has to give the same answer over again,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. And he showcased his debating skills when he replied to persistent <ORGANIZATION> Repulican </ORGANIZATION> claims that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was entitled to have the nomination confirmed as a matter of presidential prerogative. If they serve long enough, he said, all senators of both parties `` will inevitably contradict ourselves. We will meet ourselves coming around the corner on some issue.'' He cited Repulican opposition to several appointments made by former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> a decade ago and said: `` There was no talk then about the president having his own way. There was no talk then about the president winning the last election. There was no talk then about the future of the confirmation process. There was no talk then about the fairness of the process.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> also worked to thwart <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s more aggressive approach to the debate and his efforts to shake loose a few extra votes by accusing the Democrats of treating Tower unfairly. When <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> suggested that Tower be given the right to come to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and respond to allegations against him, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> immediately replied that he would be willing to give it serious consideration. By not rejecting the proposal outright, several Democrats said, the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> senator denied <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> the right to level a fresh charge of unfairness. And when <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> finally made a formal proposal on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor _ after the outcome of the struggle was clear _ <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> blocked it and the Republicans did not pursue it.
