<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The spotlight of the John Tower controversy proved hotter than <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> had anticipated and the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> senator now yearns for a chance to lower his profile. `` I'd like to go down to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and check titles on real estate for about six months,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> told reporters at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The reporters laughed and the senator smiled. But he looked like a man who meant what he said. Like it or not, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> will have to reconcile himself to a prominence most politicians would relish. For the first time in his public career, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> was the target of partisan attacks from opponents who questioned his tactics and motives as the leader of the opposition to the Tower nomination. It was a trial by fire that seems to have strengthened his standing as a national figure. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may not like the role <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> played in defeating his first choice to head the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, but the president seemed as eager as <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> to get the bitterness behind him. Before the Tower debate, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> was seen as a figure apart from politics. `` Respected'' was the word most often used to describe the bespectacled Georgian who had carved out a reputation as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s foremost authority on defense issues. The past couple of years saw a shift in <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s approach. No longer did he shy away from partisan jabs at the Republican administration. He mulled a run for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination and campaigned extensively for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in his ill-fated effort to regain the presidency for the Democrats. But the Tower nomination was a much more dramatic step into the thick of partisan politics. That battle over, the question he often is asked is, what next? `` I have no plans or any inclination to run for president in 1992,'' he said. `` I'd like to have s much lower profile.'' As chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> DLC </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> had the kind of forum he seems to relish _ one that features an often dry discussions of issues. Without question, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> was the dominant figure at the two-day meeting, despite the presence of three of the contenders for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination _ <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. `` When the history of the 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is written, it will be about <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. `` He represents the best that our democratic society has to offer.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>'s tribute to <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> was all the more striking for being just one of many voiced during the conference. But while <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> was bombarded with the sort of flattery that would prompt most politicians to begin thinking about their Cabinet choices, a bid for the presidency would make the fight over Tower seem gentle. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> represents his party's most conservative wing. While he commands unquestioned respect on defense issues his support for the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> economic program would and his conservative positions on other domestic issues would raise bitter opposition from the party activists who still control the presidential nominatin