<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some people think they have space problems when the hall closet wo n't take one more winter coat or when there's no more room in the attic for grandma's collection of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographics </ORGANIZATION>. That's nothing. The Field Museum of Natural History is trying to cope with 2 million beetles, 9.6 million insect specimens, 1.7 million fish, 381,000 birds, 2.4 million plants, a half-million fossils, 600,000 artifacts _ 20 million specimens in all with 400,000 more coming in each year. `` We're approaching a sort of gridlock,'' said the museum's geology department chairman, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolt </PERSON> The botany department bulges with twice as many plant specimens as it was designed to hold. And the geology department is cramming so many fossils into storage drawers that some may get damaged. The museum, which says its holdings are widely used by researchers, is planning to close two courtyards inside the building for construction of more storage, and is considering building four underground, two-story vaults.
