<FIRST>u w AM-BudgetTalks Bjt   03-12 0992</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget Talks, Bjt,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>Where There's Smoke, There's Mirrors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All the budget talk now going on wo n't shrink the deficit much unless <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and congressional leaders conquer a pervasive feeling that it's politically best to let the problem slide until next year. `` The smarter strategy would be to take the strong steps now,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` But I'm not kidding myself. Right now the votes are not there ... for that kind of package.'' Fiscal policy experts agree it's better to reduce the deficit while the economy is strong. Government statistics last week showed unemployment at a 15-year low, and other signs are positive. A new round of negotiations on the fiscal 1990 budget, with <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> and senior members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget committees, began Thursday and will resume Tuesday. `` There is still a great deal of hope and we're working together,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, senior Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. But the politicians have proven themselves unable to act without some kind of calamity that creates public pressure, such as the 1987 stock market crash that forced a modest, two-year budget agreement between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. No such crisis now exists. People `` do n't see the greater evil lying out there from inaction,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON>, director of the non-partisan <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. The budget negotiators `` do n't have any outside pressure either from the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people or the economy to bolster up their backbone.'' <PERSON> Reischauer </PERSON>, who became <ORGANIZATION> CBO </ORGANIZATION> director two weeks ago, agrees with the many economists who believe the deficit probably wo n't cause an immediately perceptible crisis as it gradually gnaws away at <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economic strength. `` In an abstract sense, the vast majority of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people think something should be done,'' he said. But unless there's a crisis such as a Wall Street crash or runaway inflation, `` they are not willing to admit that they or their programs should be a part of the solution.'' `` There's a key element missing from the budget debate. And that's a reason to act,'' said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Collender </PERSON>, a former staffer on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget committees who now monitors federal economic policy for the firm of Price Waterhouse. The Gramm-Rudman law was designed to create artificial crisis and force action, using the threat of across-the-board spending cuts if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president failed to meet pre-set deficit limits. But those ceilings depend on White House forecasts for the economy and government spending. And, critics say, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s fiscal 1990 budget falls back on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s habit of manipulating those forecasts to minimize tough budget choices For example, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to bail out the savings and loan industry was created to be `` off-budget.'' Tens of billions of dollars of costs thus do not show up on the balance sheets, and the administration can claim it is meeting the Gramm-Rudman goal of a deficit no larger than $ 100 billion in the new fiscal year. `` Spending saves money. Up is down. Black is white ... This is an all-time low water mark in terms of kidding ourselves,'' said <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> a </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, who also cited the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget reliance on projections of sharply lower interest rates _ at the same time rates are going up. With <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> unwilling to confront the deficit head-on, `` all of the incentives are for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to buy additional smoke and mirrors'' to avoid unpopular spending cuts or challenging <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to a tax increase, she said. `` I fearlessly predict the deficit next year wo n't be much lower -LRB- than this year -RRB-,'' she said. The deficit has actually gone up in the last two years despite much-ballyhooed plans that were supposed to reduce it. The government now expects red ink to exceed $ 170 billion this fiscal year, although Gramm-Rudman called for $ 136 billion. Further hindering bold moves this year, especially from the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, is political distrust. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> told reporters last week he has assured Democrats the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> would step forward and share blame for unpopular parts in a budget package. But there is widespread doubt among the opposition party that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would control such partisans as <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZAT