<FIRST>r w AM-GovernmentbyCommission     03-12 1022</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Government by Commission,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>It Often Produces More Rhetoric Than Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nine-member congressional commission recently recommended a 50 percent pay raises for judges, government officials and lawmakers. Nobody got a penny of it. A 14-member commission created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> labored for a year on ways to reduce the federal deficit. It ended hopelessly deadlocked. Now an eight-member commission appointed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to come up with ethical standards applying equally to all three branches of government has reported that it ca n't be done. The ethics panel report released Friday is one more bit of evidence that sometimes the commissions government creates to help with its problems produce more rhetoric than results. `` As a mayor or a governor or a president or a legislative body that is being criticized for something looks for something to do, one of the easiest things to do is to study the matter, to create a commission,'' said <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON>, a former secretary of defense and a member of the deficit reduction panel. `` Some serve a useful purpose, some do n't,'' he added. As <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON> noted, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has no monopoly on the idea of a study panel. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Pisciotte </PERSON>, a professor of government at <ORGANIZATION> Wichita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, studied commissions created by the city of <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>. `` The term I would use for some of them is the politics of avoidance, that if the governing body does n't want to deal with a particularly sensitive problem itself, it will create a board or commission or task force and pass the heat, so to speak,'' <PERSON> Pisciotte </PERSON> said. Although <PERSON> Pisciotte </PERSON> studied the phenomenon in his own back yard, he thinks his conclusions also would apply to many federal commissions. `` I think the pay commission was a prime example that was too politically sensitive, too politically difficult ... so the people who were ultimately responsible for that passed the heat,'' he said. As to why some commissions produce more results than others, experts say there is no single answer. One of the most successful commissions in recent years was the 15-member <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION>, created by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in 1981, which prepared the blueprint for a Social Security rescue bill that barreled through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in a matter of weeks. Contrasting this with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that made the deficit study, <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON> said: `` The difference was that the environment for a compromise solution on Social Security was hospitable. They really felt that they needed some mechanism to come together with a compromise package.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, on the other hand, was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the wake of the October 1987 stock market crash amid considerable speculation that it would recommend some kind of tax increase. By the time it wound up its work, the market had rebounded and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who had criticized the panel during the campaign and vowed to continue <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s opposition to any tax hike, was president. `` The only reason that thing was appointed was that you had President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who talked a great game and did some wonderful things for the country, but added a trillion dollars of debt because he basically was a compromiser and he did n't want to use the veto,'' said one Republican who has served on a number of government commissions. He spoke on the understanding his name not be used. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Janda </PERSON>, a professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said he believes a legal requirement that the commission's meetings be public added to its difficulties. `` To the extent that partisanship is a major variable, I think that open hearings become a real problem, because if you make any kind of tactical concession it can be interpreted by your rivals within the party as giving away something,'' <PERSON> Janda </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, president of the giant <ORGANIZATION> Morrison-Knudsen </ORGANIZATION> heavy construction firm, who served on the equally politically charged and equally open pay commission, said, `` I personally believe that open meetings are OK. I think they serve a useful purpose.'' The Commission on Executive, <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salaries </ORGANIZATION>, which came up with the 50 percent pay hike that lawmakers turned down in the face of a public uproar, was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1967. It is commonly called the quadrennial commission because it makes its recommendations every four years. In 1981, the commission recommended a 22 percent pay hike and outgoing President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> approved it. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had given his unofficial approval before taking office, but later changed his mind and withdrew his OK. In 1985, the commission's recommendations did result in a raise, bringing congressional salaries to $ 75,100 a year. Members of the current commission still defend their recommendations, although <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON>, a former postmaster general, conceded that `` maybe the 50 percent was a little high.'' `` We thought the administration was going to massage it a little, which they did n't, `` <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> said. `` That was a calculation on our part.'' Under the law, the president can disapprove a recommended increase or approve it either in whole or in part. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, still in office when the commission made its report, approved it in full. The ethics panel was launched by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in January with instructions to come up with standards `` equitable across all three branches of the federal government.'' It decided, however, that the basic law that prevents executive officials from taking government actions affecting their financial interests could not be applied to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for constitutional and other reasons. In addition, it was unable to decide what categories of work should be exempt from limits on outside earnings. So the panel recommended that such determinations be left up to the president. Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., chief architect of an ethics bill vetoed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last year, denounced this as `` just a terrible idea. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolsey </PERSON>, former counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a member of the ethics panel, said, `` The current commission had to work very quickly because we were asked to get the job done essentially in a month, and I think given that deadline, did a rather strikingly complete job.''
