<HEAD>GAO Study Finds Financial Management Reforms Inadequate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s implementation of financial management reforms called for in a two-year law reorganizing the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been inadequate, according to a report released Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' investigative arm, found that although the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has consolidated its financial management structure, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has made few changes and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> violated the law. The <ORGANIZATION> Goldwater-Nichols </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Reorganization Act of 1986 required that the military departments designate a single office within their civilian secretariats to conduct financial management, which includes budgeting, accounting, cash management, financial reporting, internal control and review. `` Offices within the military department secretariats and military headquarters that parallel or duplicate these functions are to be merged into a solitary office located within the civilian secretariat,'' said Rep. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study determined whether the departments' reorganizations satisfied the law and what effects the streamlining had on civilian control. `` Although the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has met the law's requirements, questions over <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> compliance remain, and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, though complying in principle, violated the spirit of the law,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mavroules </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, according to the report, merged the office of the comptroller into the office of the assistant secretary for financial management. The authority of the civilian assistant secretary was enhanced and the staff increased from 29 to about 220. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found significant reliance on `` dual-hatting'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and also discovered that the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiscal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> handled financial management. The division reports to the commandant, thus violating the law's requirment that financial management be handled by a civilian secretariat. At the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, the responsibility of financial management was consolidated within the secretariat but at the same time the position of civilian assistant secretary was eliminated and the job of military comptroller was established. The comptroller was then transferred from the secretariat to the Air Staff. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> turned the law on its head,'' <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said. `` Instead of strengthening civilian control, it bent the law by giving authority for financial management to a three-star general.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in response to the report, noted that the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has more direct control over financial management than ever before. The reorganization act was named after its chief sponsors, former Sen. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., and the late Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, D-Ala
