<HEAD>Despite Cuomo's Stance, New York May Be On Verge Of A Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state introduced the electric chair to the world in 1890 and may be on the verge of commemorating the centennial by putting it back into use after more than 25 years without legal executions. `` Even the White House is interested,'' said state Sen. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Volker </PERSON>, an upstate Republican who is chief sponsor of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s death penalty legislation in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Last week, after more than five hours of emotional debate, the Democrat-controlled Assembly approved a death penalty bill, 97-48. Of the five legislators who did not vote, two have voted for the death penalty in the past and the other three have voted against it. That means the 150-member Assembly is within one vote of being able to override a certain veto by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, which requires a two-thirds vote in each house _ that is, 100 votes in the Assembly. `` I think one of them will blink,'' predicted <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Graber </PERSON>, chief sponsor of the bill in the Assembly, of the 51 opponents. The Republican-controlled state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has voted to override <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s vetoes of the death penalty since 1985 and is expected to do so again this year. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, whose vetoes have stood for each of the past six years, has vowed to `` make my case over and over again'' against the death penalty in the next few months. Before <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> delivered six years of vetoes. But <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> acknowledged: `` it's a difficult message. People are angry and disgusted.'' The violence brought by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s crack epidemic has greatly increased public outcry for a death penalty in the state, the nation's largest without capital punishment on the books. There were 1,586 murders in the city last year through Oct. 31, compared with 1,691 in all of 1987. Statewide, <PERSON> Graber </PERSON> said during the Assembly debate, there were 2,225 murders last year, up more than 10 percent from 1987. Two weeks ago, a federal drug agent was gunned down in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. And three men are on trial for the murder last year of Police Officer <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, who was guarding the house of a witness in a drug case. Prosecutors say the hit was ordered by a jailed drug kingpin. During last year's presidential campaign, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s father gave his son's badge to pro-death penalty Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Such carnage, plus a poll showing 73 percent of his constituents favored the death penalty, prompted one long-time Assembly opponent, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>, to switch his vote last week. His represents a district in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> borough where <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> was killed. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is one of 13 states without an operative death penalty statute. Of the 37 with death penalty laws, only 13 have held executions since the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> cleared the way for them to resume in 1976; most of the others may have death sentences pending on appeal. The bill being considered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> would allow the death penalty to be used against several types of murderers, including contract killers and those who murder a police officer. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s electric chair was last used on Aug. 15, 1963, when <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mays </PERSON>, convicted of a 1961 bar shooting, became the 695th person to die in it. <PERSON> Volker </PERSON> said he's been getting calls from all over the nation about the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> situation. He said the White House asked the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office for information about the Assembly vote. Legislators say they can already feel pressure building. `` I've already gotten calls from two police officers and a detective,'' <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> Democrat who opposes the death penalty, said the day after last week's vote. `` The next few weeks will be very rough,'' said <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>. `` People have talked about this being the time to take a vacation or move away.'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said he expects to vote again against the death penalty, but he does n't flatly rule out a change of heart. `` If my district substantially lobbied me -LRB- in favor of the death penalty bill -RRB-, ... then I would have to look at it,'' he said.
