<FIRST>r a AM-Mercury-Everglades     03-12 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mercury-Everglades,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Mercury Levels In Glades Fish Alarm, Puzzle Experts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Everglades game fish are suddenly showing mercury levels among the highest ever recorded in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, alarming experts who are searching for a cause. Last week, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> issued health warnings against eating largemouth bass and warmouth caught in western parts of <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> counties. Fish samples contained up to 4.4 parts per million _ more than four times the amount of methyl mercury that the federal government considers safe. The <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> mercury is attracting attention because the precious environment there is already reeling. `` That's one of the highest concentrations ever recorded in the country,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Itri </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> expert on mercury. To find concentration up to 5 or 6 parts per million in fish, he said, he had to go back to 1970, and that was in a lake contaminated by hundreds of pounds of mercury from a factory. New tests have been ordered all over southeastern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in the wake of the unexpected findings. Scientists are puzzled by the discovery of methyl mercury in the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>. While the poisonous metal has been found frequently in the heavily industrialized <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION>, it has n't been found much in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s rural swampland. Mercury, which is especially dangerous to an unborn fetus, can cause central nervous system damage that leads to deafness, numbness, reduced vision, loss of coordination and trembling. Eating enough <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> fish to cause such damage would take months, but over a long enough time, poisoning would show its effects. There are many theories on how the metal entered the environment, according to scientists. Winds from other regions could have blown mercury-laden factory smoke from as far away as <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> into southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Or midnight dumpers could have thrown residue from some electronic manufacturer secretly into the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>. Another theory holds that fire, drought and rain could combine to leech the heavy metal from naturally occurring deposits in the soil. Some scientists lean toward a theory that the contaminant has lain in the muck at the bottom of the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> since before mercury was banned from pesticides two decades ago. `` This may have been something that has been down here for 20 years or so,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> epidemiologist Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Briggle </PERSON>. `` It has been that long since there was a legal fungicide using mercury.'' The likely sources would have been the sugar-cane fields that dot the area. <PERSON> Briggle </PERSON> speculates that the recent drought and water shortages have forced the water district to move water around inside the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>, disturbing the mercury-laden muck at the bottom of canals. Once the mercury was back in the water, it entered the food chain and was concentrated in the bass and warmouth predators at the top. <PERSON> Burkett </PERSON> <PERSON> Neely </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Loxahatchee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>, has doubts about the old fungicide theory, however. He notes the pattern of the findings _ none have been found north of the agricultural areas in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Okeechobee </LOCATION> _ suggest the contamination began more recently at a specific point or points. In addition, while the drought is serious, other years have been as bad. Yet as recently as three years ago, fish samples showed far lower mercury levels. `` We had some kind of event in the last three years that has put a lot of mercury into the system,'' <PERSON> Neely </PERSON> said. `` Something happened at the north end of the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> and traveled south.'' Contamination from agriculture is one possibility. Another, he said, is the illegal dumping by someone using nearby <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Highway 27. `` There's no telling what's in those canals,'' <PERSON> Neely </PERSON> said. Although the fish show no ill effects, and people have now been warned against eating them, there still may be victims, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunford </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Game </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fresh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Several animals, including otters, raccoons and such endangered species as <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> mink, wood storks and snail kites, could be at risk from mercury in the fish they eat or in other prey.
</TEXT>
