<HEAD>Christians and Druse Battle; Beirut Airport Shut Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christian army troops and Syrian-backed Druse militiamen battled fiercely Sunday in hills above <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, a day after authorities shut down <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s only international airport. A police spokesman said the clashes erupted in the evening in and around the strategic hilltop town of Souk El-Gharb. The violence broke a cease-fire called at midnight Saturday to halt the worst fighting around the capital in two years. There was no immediate word on casualties from Sunday's artillery and rocket duels between Christian units and militiamen of Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>. Six people have been killed and 32 wounded since clashes broke out Wednesday. On Saturday, after Druse militiamen shelled the city's port and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> compound, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ordered <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s airport closed, saying it was unsafe. The order came as a rebuff to <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>, the public works and tourism minister in the rival Moslem Cabinet. He had vowed to keep the airport operating. In retaliation, the Moslem Cabinet moved Sunday to block sea traffic to Christian-controlled harbors. `` Because of escalating hostilities, maritime traffic to the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port and the port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> is henceforth declared unsafe,'' said a statement issued by the Moslem administration. There was no immediate indication of what measures were planned to blockade the ports. The Moslems have no naval force but could launch long-range artillery attacks on <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, which is 12 miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and the main port in the Christian heartland. Directors of <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airlines </LOCATION>, the state carrier, suspended flights indefinitely after a five-hour meeting Sunday at the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> airport. Hundreds of mostly Lebanese passengers crowded the airport departure lounge, then returned to the city when the suspension was announced. An airport official who requested anonymity said staff were still reporting for duty because they did not know how long the airport would be closed. `` It's a day-by-day affair,'' he said. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Balkan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> canceled its scheduled flight to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the only regular Sunday international flight to the city, the official said. Syrian, Soviet and Czechoslovakian carriers are the only other foreign airlines that regularly use the airport. Most of Sunday's fighting focused on <LOCATION> Souk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El-Gharb </LOCATION>, a mountain peak 15 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> that commands a network of roads leading from Druse-held territory to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s Christian section. Police said thousands of people huddled in basements and bomb shelters all Saturday night as the battling troops shelled <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> suburbs and 21 residential districts on both sides of the front lines in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s central mountain range. The fighting has imperiled efforts by an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers' committee to resolve a crisis that threatens the country with permanent partition into sectarian cantons. The crisis erupted when President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s six-year term expired Sept. 22 and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> was unable to elect a successor. <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> named the army chief, Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, to lead an interim milit