<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-Attitudes     03-12 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Attitudes,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adjustment Will Be Worse For Non-Union Eastern Workers _ Psychologists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> employees have the psychological benefit of venting their feeling while picketing, but non-union workers who found themselves out of work overnight will have a tougher time adjusting, psychologists say. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>, an organizational psychologist who helps major companies through mergers and cutbacks, said he has been impressed by the commitment of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unions to the 60-year-old carrier. `` Eastern means something to them,'' said Marks, a consultant in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> office of <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> <PERSON> Meidinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>. `` I am impressed by the extent in which people want to buy into their company psychologically.'' The union's tactic of focusing attention on <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, as the bad guy in the strike that virtually grounded the Miami-based airline is beneficial for the employees, he said. `` What's fascinating about this case is it really comes down -LRB- to -RRB- a personality battle. You do n't hear people talking about the economics of the situation,'' he said. `` That's part of the reason they're rebelling against <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and not Eastern. It's this raider <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> who would come in and try to break them.'' But all Eastern employees must face the changes that in less than a week landed the nation's seventh-largest airline in bankruptcy court. `` You lose all sense of control,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziller </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> psychology professor. `` But in a way they're sustained by the fact they have a common opponent -LRB- Lorenzo -RRB- People have been known to endure five years of bombing under those circumstances.'' Since many Eastern employees have long service with the carrier, `` they have to make almost a midlife, midcareer transition, which is very, very difficult,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCabe </PERSON>, an associate professor of labor relations at the <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> school of business. An employee's standard of living `` gets cut drastically and they're eating hot dogs. ... You're going from a very high standard of living to one that's very low,'' he said. About 9,500 of the company's non-union workers ended up in the worst psychological position of all when they were laid off without notice last week, but some experts believe they will have an easier time finding work because they have more flexible skills than the pilots, machinists and flight attendants trained for a single job. Marks suggested group discussion sessions for non-union workers to vent their feelings, an avenue union members have at the union hall and on picket lines. Eastern workers will go through stages of denial, expecting the strike to be over soon, to anger against <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and the strikers, to planning strategy about staying with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and job hunting, to `` acceptance, and you've got to go through those stages,'' <PERSON> Marks </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McCabe </PERSON> expects a transition time of six months to a year while people find new jobs. He and Marks likened the strike to recent mergers and corporate cutbacks because of the similar labor adjustments. `` If you have a massive downsizing, you're truly changing the organization. It can not not change,'' said <PERSON> Marks </PERSON>, who acted as a consultant as <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> absorbed <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 and helped with the creation of the <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> corporation. `` There's a myth that some managers hold -LRB- that -RRB- the people will be grateful that they survived,'' he said. `` But that's the farthest from the truth because ... they're waiting for the other shoe to drop.'' Marks believes corporations have responsibility to help their employees to adjust and employees need to take greater control of their lives. `` The lesson to be learned for all employees is you've got to be more responsible, to be more alert to what changes will come down the pike,'' he said. `` The lesson to be learned by employers is to send a message that their people matter.''
