<HEAD>President Says He Is Healthy Again, Hopes To Quell Power Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> denied Sunday that he is involved in a power struggle with his heir apparent, and he said he is ready to resume work following a stroke. In his first televised remarks since his Jan. 18 stroke, the 73-year-old <PERSON> Afrikaner </PERSON> said he has a constitutional duty to continue in office. He made no reference to calls for him to step down when he spoke in a 15-minute, prerecorded interview on state television network's evening news show Two weeks after his Jan. 18 stroke, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> resigned as leader of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and was succeeded by Education Minister F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, 52. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> and other senior Nationalist leaders met <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> last week amid reports a solid majority of the party's parliamentary caucus wants <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to retire promptly or cede a significant share of power to de Klerk. More talks are expected this week. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who showed no signs of ill-health during the interview, said <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> `` was being misused by some people,'' but insisted there is no personal conflict. `` That would be a terrible charge against he and I,'' said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, noting he appointed de Klerk to key parliamentary posts in past years. `` Why? Because I have faith in him,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. He indicated he was displeased with suggestions a de Klerk presidency would herald a new era of political reform. `` I originated the concept of reform,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. `` Mr. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> has always shared these sentiments with me,'' he added. `` There are forces in this country seeking to exploit an unfortunate situation to sow political confusion.'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said even before his stroke, he advocated steps to l