<HEAD>LA Schools Fear Apple A Day May Not Be Best Medicine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cafeterias at the nation's second-largest school district will stop serving apples to students this week in response to a report finding a cancer risk to children from a chemical residue on some fruit. The ban also includes any apple products, including juice, pies and applesauce, said <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Unified School District officials. The district's 592,000 students have eaten more than 5 million apples each year, second only to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> school system, where students consumed 13 million apples. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> schools enacted a similar ban last week. `` That's a lot of apples, so we decided to do it in order to protect the health and safety of students,'' said <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> district spokeswoman <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Hain </PERSON>. The bans in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> followed a Feb. 28 report by the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which said the chemical daminozide could increase the incidence of cancer in children. Daminozide, sold under the brand name Alar, is sprayed on apple trees in the spring and acts to keep apples on the tree longer. That makes harvesting easier, improves the apples' color and firmness, and extends their shelf life. Alar permeates the fruit's skin and can not be peeled off or washed away. Apple growers have criticized the report, contending that only 4 percent of the apples sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> show any traces of Alar and that those traces fall well below federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> levels. `` It's very disturbing that <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> would arbitrarily make a decision to ban apples based on the results of one report in which the facts are not right,'' said <PERSON> Derl </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Derr </PERSON>, president of the Virginia-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a trade organization for the $ 1.2 billion-a-year industry. `` An apple a day is still healthy advice,'' <PERSON> Derr </PERSON> said. The federal <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has moved to ban Alar eventually, but has said it disagrees with the environmental group's contention that the risk from using it is so great that an immediate ban is needed. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> also criticized the group's study. The <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> school district will not serve apples or apple products until it conducts its own laboratory tests, said <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Altenberg </PERSON>, deputy director of food services for the district. `` We are taking a cautious approach to a problem that could affect the health of our schoolchildren,'' he said.
