<SECOND>BC-Theater,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Revival of `Measure for Measure' Opens at Lincoln Center</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Measure for Measure,'' the darkest of <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s comedies, deals with sexual hypocrisy, political intrigue and urban lawlessness. In other words, a perfect play for our times, a fact reinforced by the clear, concise, modern-dress production that opened last week at the <ORGANIZATION> Mitzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newhouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Center </LOCATION>. The director is <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>, artistic head of the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> built his regional theater reputation in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> on a series of dazzling interpretations of Shakespeare including a debonair, 1930-ish `` Twelfth Night,'' a surrealistic and phantasmagorical `` Pericles'' and a lavish `` Hamlet,'' starring <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. The latter looked like a series of staged photo opportunities for the evening news. His `` Measure for Measure'' is more austere, almost antiseptic in design and execution. Designer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON>'s minimalist environment consists of a white, graffiti-covered wall, a naked light bulb hanging over the stage and a few pieces of what looks like secondhand office furniture. A sense of dislocation prevails. Although the setting is <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, it could be anywhere. An actor reads a German-language newspaper, but the graffiti on the wall is in English. The costumes, also by <PERSON> Conklin </PERSON>, are a mixture of Madison Avenue conservative and <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION> chic. For a comedy, `` Measure for Measure'' mostly stays somber until the end of the evening. Until then, audiences have to deal with the machinations of the <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> who leaves his kingdom in the hands of <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>, a self-righteous bureaucrat. When <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> orders <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> to be executed for his sexual escapades, he does n't realize he will fall in love with the condemned man's sister <PERSON> Isabella </PERSON>. <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> offers a reprieve in exchange for sexual favors from the woman. It takes the Duke, disguised as a friar, quite a while to straighten out the mess. <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Cariou </PERSON>'s paternal portrayal of the Duke is fine, but his speaking voice is odd, slow and measured as if he were reciting a foreign language lesson. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, looking like a young, eager Wall Street lawyer, projects the coldness of the ambitious <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> as well as his frantic desire when the man realizes that he wants <PERSON> Isabella </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitford </PERSON> projects the passion of a young man afraid to die. A sweet-faced <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> makes a forthright heroine, particularly when she is standing up to <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON>'s lechery. She's also beguiling as she gradually realizes she is falling in love with the Duke. Their embrace at the end of the play is a triumph of the romantic spirit that, until then, has been overshadowed by lust. <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON> minimizes the comic characters here, but there are some expert comic cameos by <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> as a blowzy, aging prostitute and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Weston </PERSON> as <PERSON> Pompey </PERSON>, that experienced bawd turned apprentice executioner. <PERSON> Weston </PERSON> seems as comfortable and proficient with <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> as he does with television sitcom, a remarkable accomplishment. Several of the minor characters are at odds with <PERSON> Lamos </PERSON>' unfussy direction particularly <PERSON> Reggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> as an overly mannered pimp and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ikeda </PERSON> as a grating, one-note policeman. `` Measure for Measure'' always has been called one of <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s problem plays because of its juxiposition of comedy and tragedy. Both are very near the surface of this dissection of sexual and governmental power. It's to the credit of the director and his fine cast that the right balance has been found between the two.
</TEXT>
