<HEAD>Tibetans Protest Chinese Rule in Their Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police wielding bamboo canes pushed back <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> women who tried to march to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Sunday to protest Chinese rule and violence in their homeland. About 20 women sustained scrapes and scratches, either from the police officers' bamboo canes or from falling on the gravel when they tried to push through a metal barricade. Parliament was not in session at the time. Clashes between <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> demonstrators and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> police last week in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s capital, left 16 people dead and more than 100 wounded by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official count. Western travelers said the death toll was higher and could be 20 or 30. The killings occurred during protests that began a few days before the anniversary of the March 10, 1959 uprising in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> that was quashed by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Sunday's demonstration in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> was timed to coincide with the 30th anniversary of the day thousands of <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> women staged freedom marches in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> as men stayed indoors out of fear for their safety. On March 17, 1959, the Tibetans' spiritual and temporal leader, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, fled across the <LOCATION> Himalayas </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, where he remains in exile with about 100,000 other Tibetans. After <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> police thwarted Sunday's march about a mile from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, about 200 women staged a peaceful protest beside <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> Gate, the huge stone arch honoring Indian soldiers who died in the service of their British colonial rulers. As they chanted slogans calling for an end to Chinese rule, at least a half-dozen of the women fainted in the midday sun and were carried to shade trees by young women wearing T-shirts that read `` Free Tibet'' and `` Stop Repression in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>.'' The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, revered by Tibetan Buddhists as their god-king, has said he would accept Chinese control of military and foreign policy in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> in exchange for greater autnomy. Tibetans say their homeland was independent before the Chinese invasion in 1949, but <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> maintains it had been an integral part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for centuries.
