<HEAD>Researchers Find Link Between Sex Hormones and Skeletal System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli researchers have found a link between sex hormones and the skeletal system of animals, opening the way to a better understanding of osteoporosis, the <ORGANIZATION> Weizmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. The findings could help explain the high incidence of the degenerative bone disease in women following menopause, a statement from the institute said. The institute discovered in recent experiments with laboratory rats that the skeletal system responds to the animal's main sex hormone, the institute's statement said. Osteoporosis is characterized by increased porousness and brittleness in bones associated with the loss of calcium. It leads to an increased risk of fracture. An estimated 15 to 20 million people suffer from the disease in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> alone, resulting in an annual total of 1.3 million fractures with a mortality rate of 5 to 14 percent, according to figures from the institute. There is no known cure, only methods of slowing the progress of the disease. Although sex hormone deficiency has been associated with osteoporosis and such hormones have been used for treatment, the disease was believed to result from processes only indirectly related to hormone deficiency, said institute spokesman <PERSON> Nehemiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>. The research team was led by Professor <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> of the institute's hormone research and included his associates from <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The study is to be published in the `` Proceedings of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The research shows that bones of female rats respond biologically to the female hormone estrogen but are unaffected by its male counterpart, testosterone. In male rats, bone tissue is stimulated selectively by testosterone. But <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> added: `` the situation in bones is quite complex, and the stimulatory effects of estrogen and testosterone here are closely linked to other factors,'' including the level of vitamin D metabolites. `` The interdependence of these reactions could help explain why there has never been a clear association between the level of blood estrogen and the appearance of osteoporosis,'' <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> said. Osteoporosis is much more prevalent in women, who may undergo an 80 percent reduction in estrogen production following menopause, the institute said. It noted that men show only a moderate lowering of testosterone levels. <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> is a professor of endocrinology at the institute, which is a leading Israeli research facility in the natural sciences. It is in <LOCATION> Rehovot </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>.
