 The leaders of 45 Moslem states and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> meet Monday at a conference that will likely be dominated by Saudi-Iranian clashes over ethics and politics. This kingdom has refused to suppport <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s death order against British novelist <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, and it is not expected to change its position at the Organization of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. The Saudis also are expected to clash with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> over the question of recognition of the Afghan guerrilla government. Arab diplomatic sources said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> sent a delegation to <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION> on Saturday for meetings to set the agenda for the four-day conference but that the delegation returned to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> without taking part in the meetings. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said an <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> delegation headed by the deputy chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Propagation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Taskhiri </PERSON>, left <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> Sunday to attend the conference. Conference Secretary-General <PERSON> Hamed </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Ghabid </PERSON> confirmed the conference will take up the issue of <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s controversial novel, `` The Satanic Verses,'' which some say blasphemes Islam. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s 16 million people are mainly Sunni Moslems. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 50 million people overwhelmingly belong to the Shiite Moslem sect, long at odds with the Sunnis Most Sunnis agree with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that `` The Sa