<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON>, opera's most famous coloratura soprano, who made her Metropolitan Opera debut in `` Lucia di Lammermoor'' in 1961 to great acclaim, sang her first solo recital at the Met on Sunday and again deserved the acclaim she received. Her husband, conductor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonynge </PERSON>, was her deferential piano accompanist. <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> has spent most of her career in the bel canto opera repertoire, singing soprano parts written to show off the sound of the voice, its beauty, flexibility and accuracy, with much less emphasis on the words. She chose that type of song and aria for her recital. She's still a singer well worth hearing, who can be greatly enjoyed and appreciated. For the most part, she did n't choose flamboyant selections and she only chose two that are generally familiar. Those were <PERSON> Balfe </PERSON>'s `` I dreamt I dwelt in marble halls'' and <PERSON> Offenbach </PERSON>'s `` O mon cher amant'' from `` La Perichole. Many of the songs were extravagantly melancholy, like the first, `` Sad Likeness of my Phyllis'' by <PERSON> Bellini </PERSON>, with its line `` I have shed bitter tears over your ashes.'' Her one encore was `` There's No Place Like Home.'' As she sang it, <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> glanced up and around the opera house. The Met is n't `` ever so humble'' but it has been one of her special homes, where she is always happily greeted, for almost three decades It's interesting that even a simple tune like `` There's No Place like Home'' sounds like an aria when <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> sings it. Several of the other songs in the recital were combinations of folk and art songs. They sounded, sung by this singer, like classical art songs. <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> did n't use her first two or three songs to loosen her vocal chords. She sounded fine from the beginning. Her `` silver flute'' voice has become a bit darker but not much; the difference is heard more in added warmth. Her accuracy is phenomenal. She sang perfect trills in some of the brief coloratura passages. The two selections on the program with the most exciting coloratura were <PERSON> Ricci </PERSON>'s 1850 `` Io non sono piu l'Annetta'' and <PERSON> Massenet </PERSON>'s 1888 `` Autumn Thoughts.'' We particularly enjoyed <PERSON> Tosti </PERSON>'s flowingly melodic `` La serenata'' and the six <PERSON> Massenet </PERSON> songs. Other composers heard were <PERSON> Meyerbeer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rossini </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donizetti </PERSON>, <PERSON> David </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bizet </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chaminade </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Godard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gounod </PERSON>. Sometimes <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>'s tone sounds a bit hollow and sometimes she scoops up to notes, which is n't new. But her tone is beautiful; she is n't shrill or harsh. The capacity audience jumped up to award the singer a standing ovation.
